                  <div align="left"> 
                    <table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4">
                       <tr> 
                        <td height="63"><img src="../global/images/trans.gif" width="1" height="1"> 
                           <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td bgcolor="#000000" height="8" width="100%" colspan="3"><span class="header">The Power of: Launch Portal</span></td></tr><tr><td bgcolor="#333399" height="2" width="41%"><img src="/stccg/global/images/trek/glear.gif" width="1" height="5"></td><td height="2" width="1%"><img src="/stccg/global/images/trek/glear.gif" width="1" height="5"></td><td height="2" width="58%" bgcolor="#FF9C00"><img src="/stccg/global/images/trek/glear.gif" width="1" height="5"></td></tr></table><TABLE WIDTH="100%" CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN=2><SPAN CLASS="header">Rating </SPAN><IMG SRC="/stccg/global/images/rating/9.gif" BORDER=0></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP"><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=72"><IMG SRC="/stccg/global/images/read.gif" BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=72"><IMG SRC="/stccg/global/images/review.gif" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Author</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="../membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=5870">Paul "Papy" Pierce</A></FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP"><SPAN CLASS="header">Description</SPAN></TD><TD WIDTH="90%"><span class=text>This article will demonstrate some of the many uses of the Launch Portal Doorway card.</span></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP"><SPAN CLASS="header">Article</SPAN></TD><TD WIDTH="90%" ><span class=text>I have recently re-discovered a card from First Contact that I have never personally seen used locally, but which can be very powerful in a deck that is designed to maximize its benefits.  That card, of course, is Launch Portal.  This article is intended to target mainly the newer audience, but the veterans who may have forgotten about this card could gain from it as well.<br>
<br>
Relevant Card Texts:<br>
<br>
Launch Portal - Suspends play while you do any or all of the following: download Engage Shuttle Operations or Escape Pod; download (to one of your ships with Tractor Beam) one scout ship, shuttle or Borg sphere; and launch any or all of your carried ships (with crew). Discard doorway or place it atop Engage Shuttle Operations to protect event<br>
from nullification and extend its effects to scout ships.<br>
<br>
Engage Shuttle Operations - Plays on table. Shuttlecraft may be carried and launched   from your ships (if tractor beams and ENGINEER present) AND land on planets (requires their total RANGE).<br>
<br>
Engage Shuttle Operations: Dominion - Seeds or plays on table.  Your shuttlecraft and Jem Hadar attack ships may be loaded aboard and launched from your Dominion warships and battleships with Tractor Beam.<br>
<br>
Relevant Glossary / Current Ruling Entries<br>
<br>
Launch Portal - This doorway allows you to launch any carried ships at the time you play the doorway, even without Engage Shuttle Operations in play. It may download Engage Shuttle Operations: Dominion. See card title groups, ship types.  This doorway does not allow you to break a quarantine.  When this doorway is played during a space mission attempt to launch some or all of the crew on a different ship, the ship with the larger crew must continue the mission attempt (owners choice if tied).<br>
<br>
<br>
The Details<br>
<br>
Ok, now that all the preliminaries are taken care of, lets examine each function of the card in detail.<br>
<br>
First of all, it starts with those magical two words, &amp;#8220;Suspends Play&amp;#8221;.  This is probably the most important text on the card.  With those two words, Launch Portal becomes playable during mission attempts and even on your opponents turn.  And, since the card specifies &amp;#8220;any or all of the following&amp;#8221;, you can pick and choose which of the other functions you want to use when you play it.<br>
<br>
&amp;#8220;&amp;#8230;download Engage Shuttle Operations or Escape Pod;&amp;#8221; &amp;#8211; This is the most basic function of the card.  Whether you need to carry shuttlecraft, land on a planet, or get your crew out of a bad situation, Launch Portal is the card for you.  And it becomes even more useful once you use it to protect an ESO by allowing scout craft to be carried and/or land as well.<br>
<br>
&amp;#8220;download (to one of your ships with Tractor Beam) one scout ship, shuttle or Borg sphere;&amp;#8221; &amp;#8211; Another useful piece of card text.  Since it downloads to a location, it overrides native quadrant restrictions.  That alone, when combined with Home Away From Home, can be impressive enough.  Naturally, you are probably asking who has scout ships or shuttle craft?  Well, the affiliation list includes the Bajorans, the Borg, the Cardassians, the Federation, the Ferengi, the Kazon, the Romulans, and the Vidiians.  The Dominion has their own version of ESO, and everyone except the Borg can use the Non-Aligned scout/shuttle craft.  The fact that LP is a Doorway without a &amp;#8220;once each turn&amp;#8221; restriction means you can build a considerable fleet of small, quick, and expendable ships that can hide out on planets to avoid being attacked.<br>
<br>
&amp;#8220;&amp;#8230;launch any or all of your carried ships (with crew)&amp;#8221; &amp;#8211; I think this, when combined with the &amp;#8220;suspends play&amp;#8221; text, it the most powerful feature of the card.  With it, you can get out of all kinds of nasty situations when encountering dilemmas, especially on space missions.  However, one of the few downsides of LP is that it is very limited in its usefulness during planet mission attempts.  Here are some examples of how LP can be used during a space mission attempt: <br>
1. If your mega-crew runs into a The Higher, The Fewer, launch half your crew and take a smaller hit to your point total.  <br>
2. Did you just encounter &amp;#8220;Abandon Ship!&amp;#8221; with a damaged ship?  Use LP to launch a scout/shuttle with some crew so they can rescue the others.  <br>
3. Just have a Hull Breach?   If you can , launch some of your classification &amp;#8220;extras&amp;#8221;, and you might end up only losing one personnel.<br>
4. Want to score those big AMS points, but you would rather not risk your specialists in a mission attempt?  Attempt the mission with a normal crew who can solve the mission, then eject one of the mission solvers when you hit the last dilemma.  Once you clear the dilemma (but can no longer solve the mission), bring on the specialists for the bonus points.  <br>
<br>
The list can go on and on.<br>
<br>
However, the benefits afforded you by this card text does not end with just dilemma encounters.  For example, if you really want to annoy a Vidiian opponent, wait until he uses his Vidiian Cruisers special download to Claw and board you ship to harvest some organs for a &amp;#8220;free&amp;#8221; 10 points.  Then, after he has announced his Organ Theft action, launch his target away from the ship in a shuttle. Yes, your opponent could discard the Boarding Claw and attack the shuttle (probably destroying it), but the results are basically in your favor: he has wasted a special download, lost the free download of a Vidiian, did not score the 10 points, AND he has to wait until his next turn to try and harvest another personnel.  You have lost one small (expendable) ship and one personnel that you would have been forced to discard anyway.  Your opponent will find that trying to keep a Boarding Claw on your ship to be somewhat difficult now that the special download is no longer available.<br>
<br>
I hope this article has either opened your eyes to the various uses for this somewhat underused card or presented a few new twists to the card that you may not have realized before.<br>
<br>
Until next time,<br>
Paul &amp;#8220;Papy&amp;#8221; Pierce<br>
<br>
